---
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import { languageAlternates } from '../lib/i18n';

const description =
  'What I check for EU AI Act readiness when you plan or run production AI: scope, risk class, data, logging, and what you can ship now.';

const alternates = languageAlternates('/eu-ai-act-readiness/', '/de/eu-ai-act-readiness/');

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebPage',
  '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/eu-ai-act-readiness/#webpage',
  url: 'https://larsullrich.de/eu-ai-act-readiness/',
  name: 'EU AI Act readiness',
  description,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  isPartOf: { '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/#website' },
  author: { '@id': 'https://larsullrich.de/#person' },
  about: {
    '@type': 'Thing',
    name: 'EU AI Act',
    description: 'European Union regulation on artificial intelligence systems.',
  },
};
---

<ContentPage
  title="EU AI Act readiness - Lars Ullrich"
  description={description}
  canonical="/eu-ai-act-readiness/"
  noteId="eu-ai-act"
  heading="EU AI Act readiness"
  eyebrow="Compliance"
  lead="The Act puts a clock and a budget on the table. You need a straight answer on whether it applies and what that means day to day."
  icon="/graphics/icon-compliance-frame.svg"
  alternates={alternates}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  localeSwitch={{ href: '/de/eu-ai-act-readiness/', label: 'Deutsch' }}
>
  <p>
    I fold this into the
    <a href="/services/readiness-audit/">Readiness &amp; Production Audit</a>.
    I'm the person who also ships the system, so the write-up stays tied to what you'll actually build. No slide deck that dies in a drawer.
  </p>

  <h2>What I look at</h2>
  <p>
    Does the planned system fall under the Act. Which risk bucket you're likely in, and what obligations follow. Data protection and governance sized to your company and use case. What you can ship now, and what needs a control or a redesign first.
  </p>

  <h2>Who this helps</h2>
  <p>
    Growing companies in DACH and the wider EU that are past the experiment slide. Also teams already live who need a re-check when usage or the rules shift. That ongoing piece sits in the
    <a href="/agent-reliability/">Reliability Retainer</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>What you get</h2>
  <p>
    A plain write-up: in scope or not, risk posture, gaps, and a practical order of work. It sits next to the audit's use-case shortlist and build / buy / skip call, so compliance and product stay in the same conversation.
  </p>
</ContentPage>
